# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-load-balancing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] The term "failover", although probably in use by engineers much earlier, can be found in a 1962 declassified NASA report.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] The term "switchover" can be found in the 1950s when describing '"Hot" and "Cold" Standby Systems', with the current meaning of immediate switchover to a running system (hot) and delayed switchover to a system that needs starting (cold).
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] A conference proceedings from 1957 describes computer systems with both Emergency Switchover (i.e., failover) and Scheduled Failover (for maintenance).
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] Systems designers usually provide failover capability in servers, systems or networks requiring high availability and a high degree of reliability.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] At the server level, failover automation usually sends a heartbeat between two servers, either through the network or through a separate connection (for example, RS-232).
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] In the most common design, as long as a regular "pulse" or heartbeat continues between the main server and the second server, the second server will not bring its systems online; however, a few systems actively use all servers and can failover their work to remaining servers after a failure.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] There may also be a third "spare parts" server that has running spare components for "hot" switching to prevent downtime.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] The second server takes over the work of the first as soon as it detects an alteration in the heartbeat of the first machine.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] Some systems have the ability to send a notification of failover.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] Certain systems, intentionally, do not fail over entirely automatically, but require human intervention.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] This "automated with manual approval" configuration runs automatically once a human has approved the failover.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] The use of virtualization software has allowed failover practices to become less reliant on physical hardware through the process referred to as migration in which a running virtual machine is moved from one physical host to another, with little or no disruption in service.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] Failover and failback technology are also regularly used in the Microsoft SQL Server database, in which SQL Server Failover Cluster Instance (FCI) is installed and configured on top of the Windows Server Failover Cluster (WSFC).
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] The SQL Server groups and resources running on WSFC can be manually failed over to the second node for any planned maintenance on the first node or automatically fail over to the second node in case of any issues on the first node.
[src:network-load-balancing/failover] In the same way, a failback operation can be performed to the first node once the issue is resolved or maintenance is done on it.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] In computing, **high-availability clusters** (**HA clusters**) or **fail-over clusters** are groups of computers that support server applications that can be reliably utilized with a minimum amount of down-time.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] They operate by using high availability software to harness redundant computers in groups or clusters that provide continued service when system components fail.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] Without clustering, if a server running a particular application crashes, the application will be unavailable until the crashed server is fixed.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] HA clustering remedies this situation by detecting hardware/software faults, and immediately restarting the application on another system without requiring administrative intervention, a process known as failover.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] As part of this process, clustering software may configure the node before starting the application on it.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] For example, appropriate file systems may need to be imported and mounted, network hardware may have to be configured, and some supporting applications may need to be running as well.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] HA clusters are often used for critical databases, file sharing on a network, business applications, and customer services such as electronic commerce websites.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] HA cluster implementations attempt to build redundancy into a cluster to eliminate single points of failure, including multiple network connections and data storage which is redundantly connected via storage area networks.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] HA clusters usually use a heartbeat private network connection which is used to monitor the health and status of each node in the cluster.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] One subtle but serious condition all clustering software must be able to handle is split-brain, which occurs when all of the private links go down simultaneously, but the cluster nodes are still running.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] If that happens, each node in the cluster may mistakenly decide that every other node has gone down and attempt to start services that other nodes are still running.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] Having duplicate instances of services may cause data corruption on the shared storage.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] HA clusters often also use quorum witness storage (local or cloud) to avoid this scenario.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] A witness device cannot be shared between two halves of a split cluster, so in the event that all cluster members cannot communicate with each other (e.g., failed heartbeat), if a member cannot access the witness, it cannot become active.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] Not every application can run in a high-availability cluster environment, and the necessary design decisions need to be made early in the software design phase.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] The most common size for an HA cluster is a two-node cluster, since that is the minimum required to provide redundancy, but many clusters consist of many more, sometimes dozens of nodes.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] The attached diagram is a good overview of a classic HA cluster, with the caveat that it does not make any mention of quorum/witness functionality (see above).
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] The terms *logical host* or *cluster logical host* is used to describe the network address that is used to access services provided by the cluster.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] This logical host identity is not tied to a single cluster node.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] It is actually a network address/hostname that is linked with the service(s) provided by the cluster.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] If a cluster node with a running database goes down, the database will be restarted on another cluster node.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] HA clusters usually use all available techniques to make the individual systems and shared infrastructure as reliable as possible.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] These features help minimize the chances that the clustering failover between systems will be required.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] In such a failover, the service provided is unavailable for at least a little while, so measures to avoid failover are preferred.
[src:network-load-balancing/high-availability-cluster] Systems that handle failures in distributed computing have different strategies to cure a failure.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:network-load-balancing/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] In its simplest implementation, round-robin DNS works by responding to DNS requests not only with a single potential IP address, but with a list of potential IP addresses corresponding to several servers that host identical services.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] The order in which IP addresses from the list are returned is the basis for the term *round robin*.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] With each DNS response, the IP address sequence in the list is permuted.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Traditionally, IP clients initially attempt connections with the first address returned from a DNS query, so that on different connection attempts, clients would receive service from different providers, thus distributing the overall load among servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Some resolvers attempt to re-order the list to give priority to numerically "closer" networks.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] This behaviour was standardized in RFC 3484 during the definition of IPv6.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] When applied to IPv4, a bug in Windows Vista caused issues and defeated round-robin load-balancing.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Some desktop clients do try alternate addresses after a connection timeout of up to 30 seconds.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS is often used to load balance requests among a number of web servers.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] For example, a company has one domain name and three identical copies of the same web site residing on three servers with three IP addresses.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] The DNS server will be set up so that domain name has multiple A records, one for each IP address.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] When one user accesses the home page it will be sent to the first IP address.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] The second user who accesses the home page will be sent to the next IP address, and the third user will be sent to the third IP address.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] In each case, once the IP address is given out, it goes to the end of the list.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] The fourth user, therefore, will be sent to the first IP address, and so forth.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] A round-robin DNS name is, on rare occasions, referred to as a "rotor" due to the rotation among alternative A records.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Although easy to implement, round-robin DNS has a number of drawbacks, such as those arising from record caching in the DNS hierarchy itself, as well as client-side address caching and reuse, the combination of which can be difficult to manage.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS should not solely be relied upon for service availability.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] If a service at one of the addresses in the list fails, the DNS will continue to hand out that address and clients will still attempt to reach the inoperable service.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Round-robin DNS may not be the best choice for load balancing on its own, since it merely alternates the order of the address records each time a name server is queried.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Because it does not take transaction time, server load, and network congestion into consideration, it works best for services with a large number of uniformly distributed connections to servers of equivalent capacity.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Otherwise, it just does load distribution.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] Methods exist to overcome such limitations.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] For example, modified DNS servers (such as lbnamed) can routinely poll mirrored servers for availability and load factor.
[src:network-load-balancing/round-robin-dns] If a server does not reply as required, the server can be temporarily removed from the DNS pool, until it reports that it is once again operating within specs.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Weighted round robin is a generalisation of round-robin scheduling.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Whereas round-robin cycles over the queues or tasks and gives one service opportunity per cycle, weighted round robin offers to each a fixed number of opportunities, as specified by the configured weight, which serves to influence the portion of capacity received by each queue or task.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] In computer networks, a service opportunity is the emission of one packet if the selected queue is non-empty.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] If all packets have the same size, WRR is the simplest approximation of generalized processor sharing (GPS).
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] The main ones are the *classical* WRR, and the *interleaved* WRR.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] WRR is presented in the following as a network scheduler.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] It can also be used to schedule tasks in a similar way.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] A weighted round-robin network scheduler has n input queues, $q_{1},...,q_{n}$ .
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] To each queue $q_{i}$ is associated $w_{i}$ , a positive integer, called the *weight*.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] The WRR scheduler has a cyclic behavior.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] In each cycle, each queue $q_{i}$ has $w_{i}$ emissions opportunities.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] The different WRR algorithms differ in the distribution of these opportunities in the cycle.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] In classical WRR the scheduler cycles over the queues.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] When a queue $q_{i}$ is selected, the scheduler will send packets, up to the emission of the $w_{i}$ packet or the end of the queue.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] In IWRR, each cycle is split into $w_{max}$ rounds.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] A queue with weight $w_{i}$ can emit one packet at round r only if $r\leq w_{i}$ .
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Consider a situation where there are 7 packets in the first queue, **A,B,C,D,E,F,G**, 3 in the second queue, **U,V,W** and 2 in the third queue **X,Y**.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Assume that there are no more packet arrivals.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Immediately after the end of transmission of **Y**, the second cycle starts, and **F,G** from $q_{1}$ are transmitted, followed by **W** from $q_{2}$ .
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] With interleaved WRR, the first cycle is split into 5 rounds (since $max(w_{1},w_{2},w_{3})=5$ ).
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Then starts the second cycle, where **F,W,G** are sent.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Task or process scheduling can be done in WRR in a way similar to packet scheduling: when considering a set of n active tasks, they are scheduled in a cyclic way, each task $\tau _{i}$ gets $w_{i}$ quantum or slice of processor time .
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Like round-robin, weighted round robin scheduling is simple, easy to implement, work conserving and starvation-free.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] If the queues have packets of variable length, the part of the bandwidth received by each queue depends not only on the weights but also on the packet sizes.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] If a mean packets size $s_{i}$ is known for every queue $q_{i}$ , each queue will receive a long-term part of the bandwidth equal to ${\frac {s_{i}\times w_{i}}{\sum _{j=1}^{n}s_{j}\times w_{j}}}$ .
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Since IWRR has smaller per-class bursts than WRR, it implies smaller worst-case delays.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] WRR for network packet scheduling was first proposed by Katevenis, Sidiropoulos and Courcoubetis in 1991, specifically for scheduling in ATM networks using fixed-size packets (cells).
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] The primary limitation of weighted round-robin queuing is that it provides the correct percentage of bandwidth to each service class only if all the packets in all the queues are the same size or if the mean packet size is known in advance.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] In the more general case of IP networks with variable-size packets, to approximate GPS, the weight factors must be adjusted based on the packet size.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] That requires estimation of the average packet size, which makes a good GPS approximation hard to achieve in practice with WRR.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Deficit round robin is a later variation of WRR that achieves better GPS approximation without knowing the mean packet size of each connection in advance.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] More effective scheduling disciplines were also introduced, which handle the limitations mentioned above (e.g., weighted fair queuing).
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Weighted round robin has been adopted by several real-time operating systems (RTOSes) as a task scheduling strategy, where task weights determine the proportion of CPU time allocated to each thread.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] Notable examples include SuperTinyKernel RTOS, a bare-metal C++ RTOS for embedded systems, which implements a *Smooth Weighted Round Robin* (SWRR) strategy.
[src:network-load-balancing/weighted-round-robin] This results in more uniform CPU utilisation and lower scheduling jitter compared to classical WRR, at the cost of a moderately more complex scheduling calculation per context switch.
